		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><addressee>Rev. Mr. Leeser</addressee></p>
				<p>Dear Sir&#33;</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">I shall answer to your note which<lb/> you appended to my letter as soon as my second<lb/> letter on the subject will be published.</p>
				<p>I am very sorry to read that an other <add>Hebrew</add> has<lb/> been elected in <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>&#59; I think the<lb/> affairs have not been managed in a proper way&#59;<lb/> I know for sure that you have many friends in<lb/> <placeName>P.</placeName>&#59; I hope this will not discourage you&#44; and you<lb/> will after all not retire from public business&#44;<lb/> and I am convinced <add>Hebrew</add>&#59; the public<lb/> will and must acknowledge&#44; that you were always<lb/> the banner&#45;bearer of our Faith&#44; and though it<lb/> is unpleasant to be set aside&#44; still the conscious&#45;<lb/>ness&#44; that you did not deserve it&#44; is a prompt<lb/> satisfaction.</p>
				<p>Peace and order have returned among the<lb/> Israelites of our City&#44; and every past event is<lb/> almost entirely forgot&#59; my Synagogue is again<lb/> so much visited&#44; that many have to go of<lb/> because of want of room&#59; while the other<lb/> Synagogues are very little visited but by their<lb/> own members&#59; you see <add>Hazan</add>.  Go on<lb/> and care for nothing.  The first day of <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> was devoted to service and the afternoon to the<lb/> examination of my happy little band&#44; which<lb/> gave general satisfaction&#59; I was delighted to see<lb/> how my former scholars&#44; children of my severest<lb/> enemies&#44; set there so attentively&#44; and surrounded<lb/> me as affectionate as ever before.  Let those be<lb/> grown up and <add>Hebrew</add>.  The members of our<lb/> choir gave a concert last night&#44; which was<lb/> visited by a very numerous and respectable<lb/> audience&#44; and every one was pleased by it.</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>It is <sic>extremly</sic> delightful to hear children of 12<lb/> to 14 years sing the most difficult passages<lb/> with such a precision and readiness as they did.<lb/>  Great praise is due to the Gentlemen of the choirs<lb/> they spare neither their time nor their money<lb/> to elevate the <sic>hebrew</sic> music&#59; and I ardently<lb/> hope that the young people in other places<lb/> might follow this example.</p>
				<p>At a meeting of our Congregation <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> it was passed&#44; that the institution of a <add>Hebrew</add><lb/> be abolished in this Congregation&#59; all singing<lb/> to be done by the choir&#44; according to <persName>Sulzer&#39;s</persName>&#44;<lb/> <persName>Naumburger&#39;s</persName> or other <sic>hebrew</sic> music&#59; the prayers<lb/> to be read in the common oral tunes by the<lb/> Rabbi of the Congregation&#44; who has to stand<lb/> <add>Hebrew</add>&#59; the Thorah to be read in a modern<lb/> tune of reading by one appointed to it.</p>
				<p>I saw&#44; that my friend <persName>Kalisch</persName> has thrown some<lb/> sparks of his immense erudition before the critical<lb/> world.  He will repent it by the by&#44; I am sure of it&#44;<lb/> but still I like to see him caught in that fatal<lb/> net.  Who is <persName>Miss L. R. T.</persName>&#63; <sic>a</sic> remarkable<lb/> woman indeed&#59; I should like to know some<lb/> more about her.  Where lives <persName>Mrs. R. H.</persName>&#63;<lb/>  I wish to enter in a <sic>privat</sic> correspondence with<lb/> both of them&#44; and you would oblige me giving<lb/> me their directions.</p>
			<p rend="indent(1)">Wishing you <add>Hebrew</add> and God&#39;s blessing.</p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">I remain <sic>truely</sic></p>
			<p rend="indent(4)">yours</p>
			<p rend="indent(4)"><persName role="author">Wise</persName></p>
				<p><add>Hebrew</add></p>
			<pb n="4"/>
